            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Sidi Bouzid is a Central Tunisian town and the capital of the eponymous governorate.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">The toponym Sidi Bouzid originates from the local saint and ancestor Bouzid Hleli (Bū Zēd l-ⁱHlǟli), brother of Jeziya Hleliya (Žǟzya l-ⁱHlǟlīya), which are believed to be of Algerian origin. Apart from Sidi Bouzid (Sīdi Bū Zēd), other local saints are Sidi Abdelkader (Sīdi ʕAbd il-Qǟdir), Bir-Ribbiya (Bir-Ribbīya) and Bou Shmel (Bū Šmǟl).</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">As for the tribal affiliation, the population of Sidi Bouzid belongs, among others, to the following tribal sub-groups: Ubbazid (l-Ubbāzīd), Awefi (l-ᵃʕWǟfi), Gdera (l-Gdǟra), Ouled Bou Aziz (Ūlǟd Bū ʕZīz) and Msabhiya (l-ⁱMṣābḥīya).</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Sidi Bouzid is famous as the site of the self-immolation of a young local man at the end of 2010, which was the catalyst of the Tunisian Revolution in 2010 and 2011.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve"><seg type="comment" xml:id="seg1"><ref target="comment1" type="noteAnchor">Prinoth (2017)</ref></seg> is a MA thesis comprising the essential phonological and morphological features of the dialect of Sidi Bouzid, with a 9 pages-section on the lexis.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Moreover, the dialect of Sidi Bouzid is linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project.</p>
            </div>
